term_inventory_greek.meaning:
sorrow, grief, pain
pain, distress, Jn. 16:21;
grief, sorrow, Jn. 16:6, 20, 22;
metonymy: cause of grief, trouble, affliction, 1Pet. 2:19
LSJ: pain of body, opposed to pleasure; pain of mind, grief

(act.) to cause sorrow, grief;
(pass.) to be sorrowful, sad, distressed, grieve
to occasion grief or sorrow, to distress, 2Cor. 2:2, 5; 7:8;
passive: to be grieved, pained, distressed, sorrowful, Mt. 17:23; 19:22;
to aggrieve, cross, vex, Eph. 4:30; passive to feel pained, Rom. 14:15
LSJ: grieve, vex, whether in body or mind; cause pain or grief; passive: to be grieved, distressed

to groan, sigh;
to grumble
to groan, sigh, Rom. 8:23; 2Cor. 5:2, 4; Heb. 13:17;
to sigh inwardly, Mk. 7:34;
to grumble, to give vent to querulous or censorious feelings, Jas. 5:9
LSJ: sigh deeply; generally sigh, groan; transitive: bemoan, bewail

to mourn, grieve (over)
trans. to lament over, 2Cor. 12:21;
absolute: to lament, be sad, mourn, grieve, Mt. 5:4; 9:15; Mk. 16:10;
middle: to bewail oneself, to feel guilt, 1Cor. 5:2
LSJ: bewail, lament, especially for persons; mourn, go into mourning; passive: to be mourned for
